description:
Rewrite main.rs to assemble all components into a working application.

What: Entry point that parses config, builds auth, spawns client_task, runs eframe.

Algorithm:
1. fn main() -> eframe::Result<()>
2. Parse config: let config = Config::parse();
3. Build auth: let auth = config.auth_provider().expect('auth config');  (display error and exit on Err)
4. Build client: let client = JmapChatClient::new(auth, &config.server_url).unwrap_or_else(|e| { eprintln!('client: {e}'); std::process::exit(1); });
5. Create channels: std::sync::mpsc::channel::<AppEvent>() for task→UI, std::sync::mpsc::channel::<AppCommand>() for UI→task.
6. Run eframe::run_native:
   Box::new(|cc| {
     let ctx = cc.egui_ctx.clone();
     // Spawn tokio runtime + client task on background thread:
     let (task_tx, ui_rx) = mpsc::channel::<AppEvent>();
     let (ui_tx, task_rx) = mpsc::channel::<AppCommand>();
     std::thread::spawn(move || {
       tokio::runtime::Runtime::new().unwrap().block_on(
         client_task::run(client, task_tx, task_rx, ctx)
       );
     });
     Ok(Box::new(App::new(AppState::default(), ui_tx, ui_rx)))
   })

Defensive rules:
- Never unwrap() on client construction — print error and exit with code 1.
- Never unwrap() on thread spawn — print error and exit.
- Do not log bearer token in any startup message.

Tests: (integration: not easily unit-testable; covered by manual run and client_task tests)
